WHAT IS THIS FILE
A certified collection of formulas describing image‑space geometry and
motion. It includes linear motion blur, the 180‑degree shutter rule, the
Nyquist sampling theorem, quantum efficiency, saturation‑based ISO, the
path tracing rendering equation, subsurface scattering (BSSRDF), and
effective motion blur under stabilization.

WHY IT EXISTS
Motion blur and geometric transformations are fundamental to VFX
compositing, camera tracking, and virtual production. This file provides
a single source of truth for the equations that govern these phenomena.

HOW IT WORKS
Each equation is defined with its parameters and typical application
context. Where applicable, cross‑references to the relevant Kingdom
are given.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Motion blur simulation and removal
- Multi‑view geometry and structure‑from‑motion
- Sensor calibration (QE, ISO)
- Path tracing and global illumination.

WHO USES IT
L2 VFX Engineers; L1 Architects designing rendering and tracking
algorithms.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Eliminates discrepancies in motion blur and geometric formulas that
can cause misalignment between CGI and live‑action plates.

1. Motion Blur (Linear Subject)
   Blur_length = V * T
   V = subject velocity on image plane (px/s), T = exposure time (s).

2. Cinematic Motion Blur (180° Shutter)
   T = 1 / (2 * Frame_Rate)
   Blur_length = V / (2 * Frame_Rate)

3. Nyquist Sampling Theorem
   f_s > 2 * B
   where f_s = sampling frequency, B = signal bandwidth.

4. Quantum Efficiency (QE)
   η(λ) = n_electron / n_photon

5. Saturation‑based ISO
   S_sat = 78 / H_sat
   where H_sat = exposure (lux·s) that saturates the sensor.

6. Path Tracing (Rendering Equation)
   L_o(x, ω_o) = L_e(x, ω_o) + ∫_Ω f_r L_i (ω_i · n) dω_i

7. Subsurface Scattering (BSSRDF)
   L_o(x_o, ω_o) = ∫_A ∫_Ω S L_i (ω_i · n) dω_i dA

8. Effective Motion Blur with Stabilization
   Blur_effective = |V_subject – V_compensation| * T
   where V_compensation is the camera compensation velocity from OIS
   or gimbal.

